  "text": "The tobacco chloroplast atpB gene encoding the b subunit of chloroplast F 0 F 1 ATP synthase is co-transcribed with its downstream atpE gene for its e subunit [CITATION_1] , and transcription of the atpB/E operon starts from multiple sites [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The 20 nt region immediately upstream of the start codon in the atpB 5 0 -UTR is highly U-rich and possesses no SD-like sequence, suggesting that the chloroplast ribosome recognizes the initiation site through a novel element(s). To identify sequences necessary for the initiation of translation, an atpB-lacZ fusion mRNA was constructed starting from À244 to +169 of the atpB mRNA, which contained an almost complete 5 0 -UTR of the major atpB mRNA accumulated in tobacco chloroplasts [À255; [CITATION_4] ], and a set of 5 0 deletion mutant mRNAs were also generated ( Figure 1A ). As shown in Figure 1B , translation occurred at a relatively high level ($80% of wt) by deletion to position À53 (5D1), and at a moderate level ($40% of wt) by deletion to À25 (5D2). However, translation could scarcely be detected from the mRNA lacking the entire 5 0 -UTR (5D3). There is an upstream open reading frame (uORF) of 25 codons. The above assays also show that translation of the authentic coding region is hardly affected by the uORF. In vitro translation using two internal deletion mutants showed that the mRNA lacking the À25 to À1 region (ID1) could not be translated, whereas the mutant lacking the À53 to À25 region (ID2) produced translation products, although to a limited extent ($20% of wt). Therefore, we concluded that the region from À25 to À1 (or part of it) is essential for translation of atpB mRNAs and the 5 0 -UTR from À53 to À25 is necessary for efficient translation.",
